@using System.Globalization
@model Glimpse.Contributor.Community
@{
    ViewBag.Title = "Community - Glimpse - ";
}

<div class="jumbotron">
    <div class="container">
        <ul>
            <li><mark>Let's add icons for the services we use: GitHub for Issue List, Mailing List & StackOverflow</mark></li>
            <li><mark>The links to package authors seem broken if there is a space in their name</mark></li>
            <li><mark>Might be good to add the Twitter bird in front of Twitter handles so people know what they are without needing to click</mark></li>
            <li><mark>Random thought: let's set up play.getGlimpse.com! No reason we should have the janky URL we do now.</mark></li>
        </ul>
        <h1>Community</h1>
        <p>Glimpse wouldn't be what it is without the love and support of some awesome people from around the world. Thanks to everyone who has been involved in making this possible.</p>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="container content content-normal">
    <h2 id="reach-out">Reach Out</h2>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-sm-4">
            <h3>Issue List</h3>
            <p>Have you found a bug or something misbehaving? Tell us about it on our <a href="https://github.com/glimpse/glimpse/issues">GitHub issue list</a>.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-sm-4">
            <h3>Mailing List</h3>
            <p>Got questions about how to extend or work on Glimpse, or just want to discuss a new feature idea? Shoot it through to the <a href="">developers mailing list</a>.<mark>&lt;&mdash; add groups.google.com link</mark></p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-sm-4">
            <h3>Stack Overflow</h3>
            <p>Got general questions or just need a little support? Anything related to using, configuring or extending Glimpse can be asked at <a href="http://stackoverflow.com">StackOverflow</a>. View <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/glimpse">already answered</a> questions for even faster support.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="row">
        <h2 id="stay-up-to-date">Stay Up to Date</h2>
        <div class="col-sm-4">
            <h3>Blog</h3>
            <p>Follow along with the <a href="http://blog.getGlimpse.com">Glimpse blog</a> for important release notices, feature announcements and news.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-sm-8">
            <h3>Commiters on Twitter</h3>
            @if (Model.Committers.Count > 0)
            {
                <div class="listing-data">
                    <div class="row listing-data-comitters">
                        @foreach (var commiter in Model.Committers)
                        {
                            <div class="col-xs-4 col-md-3 text-center">
                                <a href="http://github.com/@commiter.GithubUsername" class="thumbnail">
                                    <img src="@commiter.AvatarUrl" alt="@commiter.Name">
                                </a>
                                <strong class="trim">@commiter.Name</strong>
                                @if (commiter.Contributions > 0)
                                {
                                    <div class="text-muted small">@commiter.Contributions.ToString("N0", CultureInfo.InvariantCulture) commits</div>
                                }
                                <a href="https://twitter.com/@commiter.TwitterUsername">@@@commiter.TwitterUsername</a>
                            </div>
                        }
                    </div>
                </div>
            }
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Get Involved</h2>
    <p class="text-center">Open source projects thrive on contributions from the developer community. <br class="hidden-xs" /> Would like to get involved? There is plenty that you can do to help! Here's a few:</p>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-sm-6">
            <h3>Issues</h3>
            <p>Glimpse maintains several issues that are good for first-timers <a href="https://github.com/Glimpse/Glimpse/issues?labels=Jump+In&milestone=&page=1&sort=updated&state=open">tagged as Jump In on GitHub</a>. If one peaks your intrest, feel free to work on it and let us know if you need any help doing so.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><a href="http://nikcodes.com/2013/05/10/new-contributor-jump-in/">Learn more about how "Jump In" issues work</a></li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="col-sm-6">
            <h3>New Features</h3>
            <p>For those looking to get more deeply involved, <a href="#reach-out">reach out</a> to find out about our current efforts and how you can help.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><a href="https://github.com/Glimpse/Glimpse/blob/master/contributing.md">Learn more about contributing to Glimpse core</a></li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row" style="margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 30px; ">
        <div class="col-sm-6">
            <h3>Share Glimpse</h3>
            <p>If you love Glimpse, tell others about it! Present Glimpse at a company tech talk, your local user group or submit a proposal to a conference about how you are using Glimpse or any extensions you may have written.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><a>Need inspiration? Watch some of the talks that we have given</a></li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Create an Extension</h3>
            <p>Get the best out of Glimpse by writing your own extention to expose diagnostic data that is meaningful for your applications. Creating extensions is easy, check <a href="/Help/Extensibility">the docs</a> or refence an <a href="@Url.Action(MVC.Packages.Index())">open source extension</a> to get started.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-sm-6">
            <h3>Documentation</h3>
            <p>Documentation is a key differentiator between good projects and <em>great</em> ones. Whether you’re a first time OSS contributor or a veteran, documentation is a great stepping stone to learn our contribution process.</p>

            <p>Contributing to Glimpse documentation is dead simple. To make it so easy, we're using Glimpse’s <a href="https://github.com/Glimpse/Glimpse/wiki">GitHub Wiki</a> as the entry point for documentation. GitHub Wikis provide an online <abbr title="What You See Is What You Get">WYSIWYG</abbr> interface for adding and editing the docs, completely in browser, using <a href="https://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/">Markdown</a>.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    @if (Model.Contributors.Count > 0 || Model.Authors.Count > 0)
    {
        <h2>Meet the Team</h2>
        <p>It takes a village to raise an open source project. Here's everyone who has helped to make Glimpse the best it can be:</p>
    }

    <div class="listing-data">
        @if (Model.Contributors.Count > 0)
        {
            <h3>Contributors</h3>
            <div class="row listing-data-cobtributors">
                @foreach (var contributor in Model.Contributors)
                {
                    <div class="col-xs-3 col-md-2 text-center">
                        <a href="http://github.com/@contributor.Login" class="thumbnail">
                            <img src="@contributor.Avatar_Url" alt="@contributor.Login">
                        </a>
                        <strong class="trim">@contributor.Login</strong>
                        <div class="text-muted small">@contributor.Contributions.ToString("N0", CultureInfo.InvariantCulture) commits</div>
                    </div>
                }
            </div>
        }

        @if (Model.Authors.Count > 0)
        {
            <h3>Extension Authors</h3>
            <div class="row listing-data-authors">
                @foreach (var author in Model.Authors)
                {
                    <div class="col-xs-3 col-md-2 text-center">
                        <a href="http://www.nuget.org/profiles/@author.Key">
                            <strong class="trim">@author.Key</strong>
                        </a>
                        <div class="text-muted small">@author.Value.Count packages</div>
                    </div>
                }
            </div>
        }
    </div>
</div>
